  "eprint": {
    "title": "The Risk of Outsourcing: Hidden SCA Trojans in Third-Party IP-Cores Threaten Cryptographic ICs",
    "authors": [
      {
        "name": "David Knichel",
        "email": "knichel@rub",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Thorben Moos",
        "email": "moos@rub",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Amir Moradi",
        "email": "moradi@rub",
        "affiliation": ""
      }
    ],
    "abstract": "Side-channel analysis (SCA) attacks – especially\npower analysis – are powerful ways to extract the secrets stored\nin and processed by cryptographic devices. In recent years,\nresearchers have shown interest in utilizing on-chip measurement\nfacilities to perform such SCA attacks remotely. It was shown\nthat simple voltage-monitoring sensors can be constructed from\ndigital elements and put on multi-tenant FPGAs to perform\nremote attacks on neighbouring cryptographic co-processors. A\nsimilar threat is the unsuspecting integration of third-party IPCores\ninto an IC design. Even if the function of an acquired\nIP-Core is not security critical by itself, it may contain an onchip\nsensor as a Trojan that can eavesdrop on cryptographic\noperations across the whole device. In contrast to all FPGAbased\ninvestigations reported in the literature so far, we examine\nthe efficiency of such on-chip sensors as a source of information\nleakage in an ASIC-based case study for the first time. To this\nend, in addition to a cryptographic core (lightweight block cipher\nPRESENT) we designed and implemented a voltage-monitoring\nsensor on an ASIC fabricated by a 40nm commercial standard\ncell library. Despite the physical distance between the sensor and\nthe PRESENT core, we show the possibility of fully recovering\nthe secret key of the PRESENT core by processing the sensor’s\noutput. Our results imply that the hidden insertion of such a\nsensor – for example by a malicious third party IP-Core vendor\n– can endanger the security of embedded systems which deal\nwith sensitive information, even if the device cannot be physically\naccessed by the adversary.",
    "keywords": [
      "hardware Trojan",
      "ASIC",
      "side-channel analysis",
      "time-to-digital converter"
    ],
    "category": "Implementation",
